You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back in `AppShell`

The custom button handles taps, but the user can still swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell.OnNavigating` using `GetDeferral()`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page has unsaved changes
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation dialog is async — without it, navigation completes before the user answers.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- `deferral.Complete()` must always be called (whether you cancel or not) to unblock the navigation pipeline.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap; `OnNavigating` catches swipe-back and hardware-back.
